1.	Introduction to testing
Testing is the process of experimenting with the features of a program with the goal of finding errors before delivering the product to end users. There are many reasons as to why testing is fundamental to the software design process. 
For one, testing detects bugs and other forms of unintended behaviour, which can cause varying levels of damage to the system. Additionally, it confirms that the product to be delivered is compliant with what end users asked for. Lastly, it makes maintenance easier, while also lowering time and monetary costs. By fixing errors before they cause harm, the maintenance process  becomes easier and less demanding. 
2.	Purpose of testing
As mentioned in the previous section, testing the software model before delivering it to end users helps identify bugs and other system faults that can and should be resolved before causing major issues for customers after deployment.
During testing, whether a single unit or the entire system is being evaluated, use cases are created to anticipate the different ways the system may respond to user actions. Once these use cases have been identified, the expected outcome for each is documented, outlining how the system is predicted to behave. Testers then recreate the behaviour described in each use case to determine whether the actual results conform to the expected ones. Any unexpected or unplanned behaviours that arise during testing are also documented and evaluated accordingly.
3.	Focus on testing a single component: 
 -- The Browsing Function
The selected component for testing is the Browsing Function. Given that this project is built around a marketplace where users discover items they wish to purchase, browsing is arguably the most central feature of the entire system. If users cannot effectively navigate and find listings, the platform loses its core purpose entirely, as no transactions can begin without it.
Testing the different aspects of this feature is equally critical because it verifies how the system behaves across a wide range of scenarios: whether the search returns accurate results for partial keyword matches, whether filters such as price range and category apply correctly and stack with one another, whether items marked as sold are properly excluded from results, and whether the page loads listings reliably. Ensuring all these cases are handled correctly is therefore essential to the overall quality of the software.

 -- Item listing/uploading
The second component selected for testing is item listing. As the main purpose of the marketplace is to showcase different items, it's important for us to make sure that the item uploading works well with all features and takes into consideration different cases. All items must be detailed, so include pictures, title, price so that they can be shown as close to the real life item as possible. 
Testing sees how it would react when there is missing information such as no pictures no title or information that is not valid such as negative numbers for a price.

